:"1169","1224":"1224","Abt 1234":"circa 1234","1168":"1168","1234":"1234","1145":"1145","31 August 1231":"31 augustus 1231","Duston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Duston, Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Duston, Northamptonshire, England":"Duston, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Dunston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1169–Abt 1234":"1169–about 1234","1169–1234":"1169–1234","–1270":"–1270","1190–1231":"1190–1231","1224–1304":"1224–1304","1140–1172":"1140–1172","1145–1173":"1145–1173","1190":"1190","1231":"1231","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","1270":"1270","1304":"1304","1169":"1169","1224":"1224","Abt 1234":"about 1234","1168":"1168","1234":"1234","1145":"1145","31 August 1231":"31 August 1231","Duston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Duston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Duston, Northamptonshire, England":"Duston, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Dunston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Duston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name for someone from Duston in Northamptonshire, named in Old English with <i>dus</i> ‘mound’ or <i>dūst</i> ‘dust’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement, farmstead’.","perhaps a shortened form of <i>Dustinton</i>, from Distington in Cumberland, recorded as <i>Distingtona</i> and <i>Dustinton</i> in the early 13th century, named from an obscure first element (possibly a Old English personal name) + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement, farmstead’."],"variants":[{"name":"Dustin","meanings":["English: variant of   Duston  .","Americanized form of French Canadian   Dostie  .","History: Many of the American bearers of the surname <i>Dustin</i> are descendants of Pierre de Bellot <i>dit</i> Dostie from France (see   Dostie  )."]},{"name":"Dunstan","meanings":["English:","from a Middle English personal name <i>Dunstan</i> (Old English <i>Dūnstān</i>), from <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ + <i>stān</i> ‘stone’. This name was borne by a 10th-century archbishop of Canterbury who was later canonized.","habitational name from Dunston (Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk), from the Old English personal name <i>Dunn</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’. Occasionally the name may also arise from Dunstan (Northumberland), from Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ + <i>stān</i> ‘stone’."]},{"name":"Distin","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of <b>Diston</b>, itself a variant of   Duston   with unrounding of the vowel."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Duston was born in 1169, in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Walkelin de Dunston, was 29 and his mother, Alice Austercarus, was 24. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Mary Wake. He died about 1234, in his hometown, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1169–Abt 1234":"1169–umbes 1234","1169–1234":"1169–1234","–1270":"–1270","1190–1231":"1190–1231","1224–1304":"1224–1304","1140–1172":"1140–1172","1145–1173":"1145–1173","1190":"1190","1231":"1231","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","1270":"1270","1304":"1304","1169":"1169","1224":"1224","Abt 1234":"umbes 1234","1168":"1168","1234":"1234","1145":"1145","31 August 1231":"31. august 1231","Duston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Duston, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Duston, Northamptonshire, England":"Duston, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Dunston, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1169–Abt 1234":"1169–noin 1234","1169–1234":"1169–1234","–1270":"–1270","1190–1231":"1190–1231","1224–1304":"1224–1304","1140–1172":"1140–1172","1145–1173":"1145–1173","1190":"1190","1231":"1231","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1172":"1172","1270":"1270","1304":"1304","1169":"1169","1224":"1224","Abt 1234":"noin 1234","116